[% WRAPPER h3_section id = "strawberry-perl" title = "Strawberry Perl" %]

<p>
<a href="http://strawberryperl.com/">Strawberry Perl</a> is an open-source,
free-of-charge, and usable, distribution of Perl for Windows (both 32-bit
and 64-bit), which gives you the full power of CPAN on Windows and is highly
recommended. As a result, it is now best to avoid ActivePerl, which is
proprietary and less usable.
</p>

[% BLOCK removed %]
<p>
One should also mention <a href="http://dwimperl.szabgab.com/">DWIM
Perl for Windows</a> which is based on Strawberry Perl, but contains more
interesting packages, such as a large part of Task::Kensho, the Padre Perl IDE,
Moose, and database drivers. <strong>Note</strong> that
as of March 2014, DWIM Perl for Windows was last updated only for
perl 5.14.2, which is now discontinued by the upstream perl 5 maintainers,
and so its use is not recommended until it will be updated again.
</p>

[% END %]

[% END %]

[% WRAPPER h3_section id = "mailing-lists" title = "Mailing Lists" %]

<p>
ActiveState has <a
href="http://lists.perl.org/showlist.cgi?name=perl-win32-users">a mailing
list for Win32 users</a>. Generally, Perl for Win32 questions can be
effectively answered in beginners mailing lists as well. However, this
mailing list may also prove to be helpful when dealing with Win32-specific Perl
extensions.
</p>

